`IFormFile` buffers into memory by default â€” for large files you need to **read the raw request body stream** and write to disk in chunks.

### Key changes

**1. Disable the form body-size limit and use streaming:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart boundary from Content-Type
    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary()
        ?? throw new BadHttpRequestException("Missing multipart boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize!
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/data/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fs = File.Create(savePath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);       // streams in chunks
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**2. Raise the limits** (defaults are 28 MB body / 128 MB multipart):

```csharp
// Program.cs â€” before Build()
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(k =>
{
    k.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
});
```

### Why this works

| Approach | Memory use | Mechanism |
|---|---|---|
| `IFormFile` | **Entire file** buffered | Reads full part into `MemoryStream` / temp file |
| `MultipartReader` | **~80 KB** at a time | Streams each section; you control the sink |

### Gotchas

- **Don't bind `[FromForm]`** on the endpoint â€” that triggers the default buffering model reader.
- **Kestrel vs IIS**: if reverse-proxied behind IIS, also set `maxAllowedContentLength` in `web.config`:
  ```xml
  <requestFiltering><requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="2147483648" /></requestFiltering>
  ```
- Use `CancellationToken` from `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for clean abort handling.
- Always **sanitize filenames** â€” never use the client-supplied name directly.
